segments.text: So our lodging was taken care of.
Of course, we had to provide our food.
We didn't expect them to feed us in the village.
So we'd done this tour.
Were you in a bus?
Yes, we would rent a bus.
I don't know if rent is a good word or not, because they'd furnish the driver.
We'd get through play in one place and maybe we could stay all night and drive all the next day to the next one.
But we tried to book it so that we wouldn't have too much mileage to make in a short period of time.
And these were dances for the
town people, for anybody that wanted to come?
Yes, I would suppose so.
Because generally, you know, you wouldn't have too many Aggies in one town.
West Texas is well known for its Aggie information.
And I'm sure they invite people from the next town club, you know, or whatever.
Because they're usually well attended.
So you would have, you didn't take a piano from here?
No.
So they would provide the piano, and you'd have to get accustomed to a new piano every night.
Do you remember any particular difficulties you had?
Well, I can with Buzzy, but not necessarily.
Well, give an example with Buzzy.
Well, one place in South Texas where we booked a band was
The piano was so bad and so out of tune, I just sat there all night.
All I would contribute would be a discord.
I was the worst piano I ever saw, although I was singing some pretty bad ones.
What was, in that first year or so, what were the favorite songs that the Aggieland Orchestra played?
Well, Chattanooga Choo Choo and
There were some instrumentals that he played that I don't recall quite the names of, but some of the big bands had some instrumentals to show off their talent.
He emulated some of those.
Did you all have a vocalist?
Well, not Percy.
There was a young lady here in town.
Alice Butler.
Alice what?
Butler.
She was Bob Butler's wife.
They were a big construction company.
But she had a good velocity and she used to sing with us occasionally.
But she didn't travel with you?
No, she didn't.
So mostly it was instrumental.
And of course, that was the going thing, you know, instrumental music.
Some of the bands, as you know, had very fine vocals.
They were big bands.
Now, all of the members of the Aggieland Orchestra were students.
Yes.
And did y'all ever have any problem of being out on the road and not be able to get back to classes?
No, we didn't.
I think we were very careful about that.
Because most of the dances were held either on Friday or Saturday night.
So you had all day Sunday to get back if you needed to be in class on Monday morning.
All right, let's go back to classes.
How did you, as a young 28-year-old freshman, what was it like to start college
At that age?
Well, I'll give you something.
I went to a Yale practice.
I'm not over there.
I'm not a speaker, but that YMCA thing.
Everybody's down on those steps, you know, and everything.
And they, you know, at the end of the thing, that freshman had to take off and run, and you're familiar with that, don't you?
And so the band leader now was sitting up there, and he said, now don't you run.
So I didn't, man.
But everybody thought I was about a junior transfer.
I wasn't my age.
So they didn't pick on you?
No.
What classes do you remember that first year?
What courses?
Well, mostly the baseball.
I excelled in English.
You know, I had the advantage of all the history and things and everything like that.
English, I mean, I had some, you know, what was it, I think it was history.
But mostly it was the basics.
Who taught, do you remember who taught your history class?
Well, I, yeah.
Why did you say that guy's name?
Nance.
Yeah, one of them.
But I think I got him in one of the higher grades.
What about, was it Ralph Steen?
Yeah.
Yeah.
And I don't know who else.
Let's see.
Let me think about some of those other guys.
I was good in English.
I had an advantage growing up.
I was reading and that sort of thing.
I got good grades in those courses.
What about math?
I had algebra.
pain in the neck.
If I had had advanced algebra, I had jumped in high school and it was a breeze for me.
But trigonometry I had to skip on.
I think you had to take algebra at that time.
And then a literature, I don't know if it was English literature or
That was a summer draft.
And it managed to give me 150 pages to read by the next day.
Did you go home that first year?
Did you go home to visit?
Yes, I did.
But you're hitchhiking home most of the time, you know.
You leave on Friday afternoon.
Maybe you should be on the road at midnight.
Describe your memories of hitchhiking.
Where did you go to catch the ride?
We used to line up over at A&M over in Bryan, I think, on Texas Avenue, right about the business center down there.
Over on, well, then it was not called Texas, it was called something else, I don't know why.
And you'd go and put your bag down in the place and line up, and when your time came to catch a ride.
And everybody, you know,
The public knew about the agonist attack.
So you'd get a ride with me.
Sometimes you'd get dropped off at the wrong place.
Did that ever happen to you?
Oh, yeah.
Where did you get dropped off?
So I got dropped off just out of Waco in a little small town down there.
And I think I stood there an hour before I finally got a ride.
Generally speaking, you'd get your ride pretty quick.
And my roommate lived there.
That first year it lived in Longview or Gladewater, in Gladewater.
The woman asked me to go home with her.
We got out and we caught a ride.
It was about 5 or 6 o'clock that afternoon.
One of our rides, we had to ride in a turtle, you know one of them.
And the wind was blowing strong and we were just about to blow out of that thing.
Finally, somewhere up in East Texas, we saw the ride that took us all the way to Gladewater.
And we got there about midnight.
Did you ever have any bad hitchhiking experience?
No, not really.
Pretty much, you know, people know you about baggage.
And I don't know why they made special provisions.
So at that time, we were lucky.
This is where we're going.

alright so did you go home thanksgiving or Christmas your first year I'll be there you know you yeah it wasn't too much and who are some teachers that you remember from that first year so that we're really special well remember
You mentioned one of them, Screaming Al.
Screaming Al Nelson in history?
Yeah.
I had him one time.
He taught me a lot.
Did you know him?
Yes, sir.
And then the English teacher, Powell.
Powell?
Uh-huh.
P-O-W-E-L-L.
He was quite an older man.
His eyesight wasn't too good.
But I turned in a paper to him one time, I don't know what it was, something written in class, which he gave me astounding numbers of hundreds.
But like I said, I had the advantage, almost impressionable, you know, of 12 years of reading and writing and writing.
And did the other students sometimes turn to you for advice since you were older than they were?
No, I never really had any of that.
I know one time, though, when I first came down here, and my roommate's name was Guggles.
And so when his parents got his first, you know, grades, his mother came down.
He said, I'm going to bring him over to Jesus.
And you see that he does his classwork.
Of course, I had all I could do.
And he said, and be sure that he does what he's supposed to do.
And I can remember when I told her, you're going to need to put this down.
So if he doesn't do right, I'll just stick the hell out of it.
Did they ever try to haze you, the sophomores or juniors?
No, I never had any of that.
because of my age, you know, and I'm just, I don't know what, they never, I was never hazed.
Did you eat at that, at the boarding house where you lived?
Yes, I did.
In fact, not only ate there, but behind that house they had a garden plot.
It was, I don't know how much it was, but it was a pretty good sized plot back then.
farming experience, I planted some green beans back then.
Real green beans today.
I never thought that the crops would exist before.
They just kept varying and we ate green beans over here.
Now how did you get to the campus each day?
How did you get back and forth to the campus?
Well, like I said, this one guy had a truck.
We used to ride out there.
I don't know whether he went back and forth at different times, but I do recall having ridden in that truck from time to time.
And otherwise, we had people that would pick you up and take you to school.
And I don't recall ever having missed a class because of being tardy or anything.
And did you spend the whole day on the campus sometimes?
If I haven't had more than one class, then yes.
now where did you go if you had any spare time during the day where did you go on campus to study or to relax?
mostly probably to relax and I might have hushed up on my piano where would you do that?
well they had a piano in that church type thing oh in the old chapel?
yeah they had a good piano there and they also had a good piano in the
in the YMCA there.
Did you meet Mr. Cashin?
Oh, yes.
Please describe him.
Well, he was head of the YMCA there.
Son Red was a kid then, about five or so.
We used to see a lot of Reds around the YMCA.
And I never had very much relationship with Mr. Cashin.
He was pretty busy with his stuff, I guess.
But it was okay for you to play on that piano?
Oh, yes, sir.
Did you go to the library much?
Yes, I did.
Quite a bit.
Of course, it was much smaller than it is now.
But I can't remember any researching I did there or anything like that.
But I've understood from freshmen in the Corps that the library was a place where you could go and escape the sophomores.
Well, since I didn't classify, really, as a freshman, I didn't have to do that.
Where did you go to get something to eat or a cold drink?
Well, you know, they had this.
thing down in the basement at the YMCA.
I've forgotten the name of it.
It's been there for years and years and years.
You just go down there and you get Coca-Cola and things like that.
Would you eat lunch on campus?
Sometimes I would.
Where?
At Sabeza.
I believe at that time you paid as you went in.
I'm thinking that
Do you remember what that first year or any of your years cost?
What the tuition and fees were?
And you made all of your, you supported yourself.
Your parents didn't send you any money.
Right.
But the band was better paid than most of the other students or, you know, other people.
So I can't remember whether I got $5 a day or that thing at $5 an hour.
It was probably more like $5 a day.
And on those trips, at Christmas time, you know, it kind of built up a capital fund, you know, and it got me over into it.
So you mean you're...
had a little bit of leftover.
Did y'all ever get stranded by?
Back?
No, I don't remember ever being.
I can remember.
Me and two other guys got stranded down in Dallas.
And we were supposed to be back on campus in the morning for classes, you know.
And we got stranded.
Stranded is.
I'm telling you, we got stranded down between here and, let's see, what's that?
Not in Avisota.
Hempstead.
Hempstead.
Between Hempstead and Avisota.
We got really stranded.
We didn't get home until daylight.
Oh, boy.
Now, when you went to class, since you weren't in uniform, what did you wear?
Standard pants.
Well, but was it a... Well, probably jeans and a shirt, you know, and a jacket, and work shoes.
But I must have stood out like a sore thumb, you know, in some of those classes.
In class, what was the normal kind of behavior?
How did you all behave in class?
extended the class.
There was no hot shots and yak yak death.
Those classes were, what you can understand, I'm sure, that since it was a military school, most of the students were military students and they knew what to expect of them.
Did you all go every day?
No, we didn't have classes every day.
No, but I mean, did you go to every time the class met or did you cut class very often?
No, we never cut classes.
As that first year ended, how were your grades?
Well, I just barely made it from the six-week thing.
I hadn't gotten a D in trigonometry or algebra or something like that that had sent me back home.
That was your first year?
Yeah.
I barely made it under the wire to stay that second semester.
I'll be right back.

evaluated six weeks I think that's what it was and then if you didn't make it in six weeks you were shipped out they didn't have no room for you if you couldn't make you know the grades but I was lucky and I mean I was fortunate to be able to stay that second six weeks because I just barely got in under the wire I couldn't even remember how to study I had to learn how to study before I learned how to do anything else
Who did you turn to for advice if you needed help?
Well, sometimes I'd talk to the senior guys.
But I'd impose on one of my roommates to send me my business.
And he's so busy trying to find out what that meant, he didn't have time to tell me.
By the time I got down to the nitty-gritty, I had to change forces in order to make it.
I talked to one of the counselors.
I don't know who he was, who advised me.
He said, if you can't make it in engineering, make it in something else.
So I got out of the engineering school and went into the other ladder school.
Which one?
Well, whatever, the English and all that stuff.
Oh, arts and science.
Yes.
I got a BA in that.
That's what I found at the end of that year.
All right.
At the end of your first year,
Did you go back home to McKinney that summer?
Yes, I went to work.
I got a job with Lone Star Gas Company, and we put pipelines in all over East Texas.
Do you remember what the pay was?
No, I sure don't.
It wasn't very much, though.
Who helped you get that job?
These two guys in the project house there, they were from Dallas and they knew this guy and they would, I think before they had worked for him.
And I got a job inspecting wells that we put in pipelines and they'd weld them together.
And they gave me the job of just go by and check those wells to see if there were any holes in them.
And with the sun beating down on the back of my head,
at 110 degrees, and bending over that hot well to look at that thing, boy, first day I was sick as a dog, man.
I had eaten something, I don't know what.
It was hard to digest.
Boy, they put me in the shade for the rest of the afternoon.
But you know, after that, I didn't have any trouble with eating.
So you did that all summer.
Yeah.
Then came back, and this would be, your second year would be the fall of 1941.
Yes.
And so you're now getting ready to major in arts and sciences.
Where did you live that second year?
Well, I first went back and lived in the project house.
But this man that had the truck, I guess, didn't have it anymore, didn't bring it down.
So I had to hitchhike every day.
And I had an opportunity to go into the project houses.
And as much as I hated to leave the old ladies,
I had to get someplace where I could make it.
So I moved into Project House 7, which was from Collin County or from one of those counties up there.
And I moved in with three other guys from Collin County.
About how many lived in that Project House total?
Well, there was four of us in that one room, and there was about, I guess, about 16.
Were they all from Collin County?
No, I don't think so.
It had kind of gotten diluted, you know, but most of them were from Collin County.
Four of you in one room.
Describe what was in that room.
What kind of furniture?
Well, it was stacked beds.
They had two stacked beds, and they had, I don't remember whether they had two tables or what, but they had, I think,

tables were divided you know you had lights on both and probably two two guys studied on each side of the table so and of course not everybody is studying at the same time so all right where was the shower it was upstairs and it was a communal shower and i guess probably maybe six or eight
Do you remember what the cost was to live in the project house?
Yeah.
$13 for $13 a month a month.
Yeah.
And mother, she did the cooking.
And she had somebody helping her out.
Anyway, feed 16 men, you know, three meals a day.
Yeah.
And did you have any duties?
Did you have to help clean up or wash?
Sure.
I had to make sure that my room was clean.
And I used to, Dr. Russell was the head of that thing.
Dr. Dan.
Yeah.
And he started that business.
And I used to go with him over to North Gooch, where he bought groceries from this grocery store.
He had them hauled groceries there.
And then they had a grocery store.
a place there in the area where it's also stocked up on the food.
But could you imagine room and board at $13?
I think it finally went up, but $13 a month.
Did he go to North Zulch to buy groceries for the project houses?
And you helped him haul that.
Yes.
Did he get it from the railroad car?
Or was there a grocery grocery place over there?
I don't know how they how they managed to use that place.
But I can recall we went over there and we load up a big truck.
Describe Dr. Russell's personality.
What kind of a man was he?
He was a wonderful man.
He's very thoughtful.
And, and he had to be
a fine man to do all that and start that thing.
Poor guys like me and 900 others could go to a place of higher learning without spending their life savings so to speak.
Describe him physically.
What size was he?
He was a big man.
What did he look like?
As I recall, he was brunette, and at that time, I think he was probably in his sixties or so.
He had a heavy set and everything, and dark hair.
He had me in the wagon, you know, in our old bundles and things.
Well, we got to that interurban station, not the station.
We were talking about your freshman year and you worked for the gas company that fall and then came back
and lived in the project house, did you and the others in the project house, did you all do any house cleaning?
We had to clean our own windows.
And I believe that we were assigned kitchen duties.
You know, we had a week in which we had to go in the kitchen and wash dishes or whatever we had to do in the kitchen.
Did you ever bring down from your family, did you ever bring part of the groceries?
Yes.
What did you bring?
Mainly garden stuff, which was hard to get down there.
My mother was a good gardener.
And all the other guys did the same thing.
Whatever they had, eggs, you know, they might be helpful to add up to food.
What, in that project house, what was not allowed?
What were you all not to do in that house?
You couldn't bring your drugs.
Okay.
And, I don't know, everybody had to respect everybody else's, you know, their space and their people.
Did anybody drink in the house?
Oh, no.
Oh, no.
Not any of that is going on.
What about smoking?
Did you young men smoke in those?
In fact, I had been off cigarettes for 18 months.
I picked up a hat.
What was your favorite brand?
Lucky Strike.
They were the mildest ones.
And I guess the easiest ones to quit.
I finally quit when I was 39 years old.
Did y'all smoke in the house, in the project house?
I can't remember whether or not.
Probably did.
Did anybody chew tobacco in there?
Not that I know of.
No snuff?
No.
And I don't remember too many guys.
I'll say that.
You know, it's addictive.
It's addictive.
Like me, when I got back down there and started smoking, I picked up the habits.
Where did you do your washing?
They had a washout.
You'd go in there and wash.
The other thing, I guess, were the washing machines over there?
I think that's all there was to do in there.
Did it cost anything?
Yeah, I believe you had to pay.
And so you lived there all of your sophomore year?
How many years did you live in the project house?
Well, I stayed there until I went into service in 1942.
So that was two years ago.
camaraderie.
With four of you in a room, how did you all work it out that the lights would go off?
How did you keep somebody from studying into the wee hours of the night?
What were the rules about turning the lights on and off?
I don't recall.
I don't know.
It never seemed to be easy.
and nobody ever had anything stolen and you're still you were in the orchestra during all this time and still traveling
What, were they wanting German music or Czech music?
Now, some of the nationally famous big bands came to A&M.
Do you remember some of those?
Well, Stan Kenton one time, his music was far off the beat, you know, a lot of music.
But we had Stan Kenton.
We had, I don't know, I didn't know, I didn't know.
